Wassertein Generative Adversarial Network¶

This part is an evolution of the previous GAN model. The main difference is that this time the loss function is a Wassertein loss. This addresses some of the limitations of the first mode, in particular the instability of training.

Why? In the previous GAN, the generator and the discriminator are trained using the binary cross-entropy loss, which has the following problems:

  • Vanishing gradient: when the discriminator becomes too "confident", the generator receives no useful information to improve.
  • Training instability: losses doesn't seem to decrease due to the saturating nature of the sigmoid and BCE.

WGAN uses a critic that outputs real values (not probabilities), and optimizes and optimizes:

  • Critic (Discriminator) loss:

    $$ \mathcal{L}_D = \mathbb{E}_{\mathbf{\tilde{x}} \sim \mathbb{P}_g} [D(\tilde{x})] - \mathbb{E}_{\mathbf{x} \sim \mathbb{P}_r} [D(x)] $$

    The critic tries to maximize the difference between its output on fake data $\tilde{x}$ and real data $x$.

  • Generator loss:

    $$ \mathcal{L}_G = - \mathbb{E}_{\mathbf{\tilde{x}} \sim \mathbb{P}_g} [D(\tilde{x})] $$

    The generator tries to minimize the critic’s output on fake data, effectively "fooling" the critic.

Setting up the GAN¶

This first part is the one commented in the basic GAN and the same reasoning for the VAE holds

class VAE(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, config, latent_dim):
        super().__init__()

        modules = []
        for i in range(1, len(config)):
            modules.append(
                nn.Sequential(
                    nn.Linear(config[i - 1], config[i]),
                    nn.ReLU()
                )
            )
        
        self.encoder = nn.Sequential(*modules)
        self.fc_mu = nn.Linear(config[-1], latent_dim)
        self.fc_var = nn.Linear(config[-1], latent_dim)

        modules = []
        self.decoder_input = nn.Linear(latent_dim, config[-1])

        for i in range(len(config) - 1, 1, -1):
            modules.append(
                nn.Sequential(
                    nn.Linear(config[i], config[i - 1]),
                    nn.ReLU()
                )
            )       
        modules.append(
            nn.Sequential(
                nn.Linear(config[1], config[0]),
                nn.Sigmoid()
            )
        ) 

        self.decoder = nn.Sequential(*modules)

    def encode(self, x):
        result = self.encoder(x)
        mu = self.fc_mu(result)
        logVar = self.fc_var(result)
        return mu, logVar

    def decode(self, x):
        result = self.decoder(x)
        return result

    def reparameterize(self, mu, logVar):
        std = torch.exp(0.5* logVar)
        eps = torch.randn_like(std)
        return eps * std + mu

    def forward(self, x):
        mu, logVar = self.encode(x)
        z = self.reparameterize(mu, logVar)
        output = self.decode(z)
        return output, z, mu, logVar

use_cuda = 1
device = torch.device("cuda" if (torch.cuda.is_available() & use_cuda) else "cpu")
num_epochs = 300
learning_rate = 0.00003
model = model.to(device)   
optimizer = torch.optim.Adam(model.parameters(), lr = learning_rate)

hist = np.zeros(num_epochs) 
for epoch in range(num_epochs):
    total_loss = 0
    loss_ = []
    for (x, ) in train_loader:
        x = x.to(device)
        output, z, mu, logVar = model(x)
        kl_divergence = 0.5* torch.sum(-1 - logVar + mu.pow(2) + logVar.exp())
        loss = F.binary_cross_entropy(output, x) + kl_divergence
        loss.backward()
        optimizer.step()
        loss_.append(loss.item())
    hist[epoch] = sum(loss_)
    print('[{}/{}] Loss:'.format(epoch+1, num_epochs), sum(loss_))

In [13]:
def sliding_window(x, y, window):
    x_ = []
    y_ = []
    y_gan = []
    for i in range(window, x.shape[0]):
        tmp_x = x[i - window: i, :]
        tmp_y = y[i]
        tmp_y_gan = y[i - window: i + 1]
        x_.append(tmp_x)
        y_.append(tmp_y)
        y_gan.append(tmp_y_gan)
    x_ = torch.from_numpy(np.array(x_)).float()
    y_ = torch.from_numpy(np.array(y_)).float()
    y_gan = torch.from_numpy(np.array(y_gan)).float()
    return x_, y_, y_gan

Setting up the WGAN¶

The same structure as for the baseline model is chosen for the generator and for the discrimator.

In [16]:
class Generator(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, input_size):
        super().__init__()
        self.gru_1 = nn.GRU(input_size, 1024, batch_first = True)
        self.gru_2 = nn.GRU(1024, 512, batch_first = True)
        self.gru_3 = nn.GRU(512, 256, batch_first = True)
        self.linear_1 = nn.Linear(256, 128)
        self.linear_2 = nn.Linear(128, 64)
        self.linear_3 = nn.Linear(64, 1)
        self.dropout = nn.Dropout(0.2)
        

    def forward(self, x):
        use_cuda = 1
        device = torch.device("cuda" if (torch.cuda.is_available() & use_cuda) else "cpu")
        h0 = torch.zeros(1, x.size(0), 1024).to(device)
        out_1, _ = self.gru_1(x, h0)
        out_1 = self.dropout(out_1)
        h1 = torch.zeros(1, x.size(0), 512).to(device)
        out_2, _ = self.gru_2(out_1, h1)
        out_2 = self.dropout(out_2)
        h2 = torch.zeros(1, x.size(0), 256).to(device)
        out_3, _ = self.gru_3(out_2, h2)
        out_3 = self.dropout(out_3)
        out_4 = self.linear_1(out_3[:, -1, :])
        out_5 = self.linear_2(out_4)
        out_6 = self.linear_3(out_5)
        return out_6

class Discriminator(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self):
        super().__init__()
        self.conv1 = nn.Conv1d(4, 32, kernel_size = 5, stride = 1, padding = 'same')
        self.conv2 = nn.Conv1d(32, 64, kernel_size = 5, stride = 1, padding = 'same')
        self.conv3 = nn.Conv1d(64, 128, kernel_size = 5, stride = 1, padding = 'same')
        self.linear1 = nn.Linear(128, 220)
        self.linear2 = nn.Linear(220, 220)
        self.linear3 = nn.Linear(220, 1)
        self.leaky = nn.LeakyReLU(0.01)
        self.relu = nn.ReLU()

    def forward(self, x):
        conv1 = self.conv1(x)
        conv1 = self.leaky(conv1)
        conv2 = self.conv2(conv1)
        conv2 = self.leaky(conv2)
        conv3 = self.conv3(conv2)
        conv3 = self.leaky(conv3)
        flatten_x =  conv3.reshape(conv3.shape[0], conv3.shape[1])
        out_1 = self.linear1(flatten_x)
        out_1 = self.leaky(out_1)
        out_2 = self.linear2(out_1)
        out_2 = self.relu(out_2)
        out = self.linear3(out_2)
        return out

WGAN Training¶

This following piece of code trains the WGAN and for it to work it needs of the following values:

  • Multiple critic updates (n_critic=5): For each generator update, the critic (discriminator) is updated multiple times to better approximate the Wasserstein distance.
  • Weight clipping (clip_value=0.5): Applied to critic parameters to enforce the Lipschitz constraint required by WGAN theory, preventing the critic from becoming too "steep" and ensuring stable training.

This values are up for optimization and if those are changed the results differ by a lot.

In [17]:
# Impostazioni base
use_cuda = 1
device = torch.device("cuda" if (torch.cuda.is_available() & use_cuda) else "cpu")

batch_size = 128
learning_rate = 0.00015
num_epochs = 200
n_critic = 5  # numero di aggiornamenti del critic per ogni passo del generatore
clip_value = 0.5  # clipping dei pesi del critic

# Dataloader
trainDataloader = DataLoader(
    TensorDataset(train_x_slide, train_y_gan),
    batch_size=batch_size,
    shuffle=False
)

# Modelli
modelG = Generator(21).to(device)
modelD = Discriminator().to(device)

optimizerG = torch.optim.RMSprop(modelG.parameters(), lr=learning_rate)
optimizerD = torch.optim.RMSprop(modelD.parameters(), lr=learning_rate)

histG = np.zeros(num_epochs)
histD = np.zeros(num_epochs)

for epoch in range(num_epochs):
    loss_G_epoch = []
    loss_D_epoch = []

    for i, (x, y) in enumerate(trainDataloader):
        x = x.to(device)
        y = y.to(device)

        for _ in range(n_critic):

            fake_data = modelG(x).detach()
            fake_data = torch.cat([y[:, :3, :], fake_data.reshape(-1, 1, 1)], dim=1)

            # Calcola output del critic
            dis_real_output = modelD(y)
            dis_fake_output = modelD(fake_data)

            # Wasserstein loss
            lossD = -torch.mean(dis_real_output) + torch.mean(dis_fake_output)

            modelD.zero_grad()
            lossD.backward()
            optimizerD.step()

            for p in modelD.parameters():
                p.data.clamp_(-clip_value, clip_value)

        loss_D_epoch.append(lossD.item())

        fake_data = modelG(x)
        fake_data = torch.cat([y[:, :3, :], fake_data.reshape(-1, 1, 1)], dim=1)

        output_fake = modelD(fake_data)

        lossG = -torch.mean(output_fake)

        modelG.zero_grad()
        lossG.backward()
        optimizerG.step()

        loss_G_epoch.append(lossG.item())

    histG[epoch] = sum(loss_G_epoch)
    histD[epoch] = sum(loss_D_epoch)
    print(f'[{epoch+1}/{num_epochs}] LossD: {histD[epoch]:.4f}  LossG: {histG[epoch]:.4f}')

rolling = 48
Returns1 = (y_train_pred[rolling+1:] / y_train_pred[rolling:-1]) - 1
SampleSize = len(Returns1)

pVAR = [0.05, 0.01]

Historical95 = []
Historical99 = []
EstimationWindowSize = int(rolling / 2)

for t in range(rolling + 1, len(Returns1)):
    y = Returns1[(t - EstimationWindowSize):(t-1)]
    
    Historical95.append(np.quantile(y, 0.95))
    Historical99.append(np.quantile(y, 0.99))
    
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))

plt.plot(Historical99, label='Historical VaR 99%', linewidth=2, color="#C00321")

EstimationWindowSize = int(rolling / 2)

for t in range(rolling + 1, len(Returns1)):

    Historical95.append(np.quantile(y, 0.95))
    Historical99.append(np.quantile(y, 0.99))
    
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))

plt.plot(Historical95, label='Historical VaR 95%', linewidth=2, color="#1446A0")
plt.plot(Historical99, label='Historical VaR 99%', linewidth=2, color="#C00321")

plt.title('Rolling Historical Value-at-Risk on test set', fontsize=14)
plt.xlabel('Time (rolling window steps)', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('VaR', fontsize=12)

# Print last-point averages

print(f'Average Historical VaR 99% (last point): {np.mean(Historical99):.4f}')

Average Historical VaR 95% (last point): 0.0134
Average Historical VaR 99% (last point): 0.0158

By adopting a more complex model what we see is that we have a lower Value at Risk. The following result can be explained by:

  • WGANs provide more informative gradients, leading to better convergence. This helps the generator learn the true data distribution more accurately, reducing the generation of unrealistically extreme returns that would otherwise inflate VaR.
  • Since VaR is a quantile-based measure (typically 95% or 99%), it is highly sensitive to the distribution's tails. WGAN-generated returns tend to follow the statistical properties of real data more closely, especially in the tails, leading to a tighter (i.e., lower risk) estimate of VaR.
